{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MRgSR9mPWbUn8PThfe9rMh","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Implementation complete. Here is a summary:\n\n**Story 9-1: Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning** -- Status: **review**\n\n**What was done:**\n\n1. **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/stack-detect.ts`** -- Added `StackDetection` interface, `SKIP_DIRS` constant (7 dirs), `STACK_MARKERS` constant (priority-ordered), `detectStacks()` function with root + 1-level subdirectory scanning. Refactored `detectStack()` to delegate to `detectStacks()` as a compat wrapper.\n\n2. **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`** -- Added 15 new tests in a `detectStacks` describe block covering all 6 acceptance criteria: dual/triple root stacks, monorepo layout, single-stack, empty dir, all 7 skip dirs, priority ordering, alphabetical subdir sorting, python marker deduplication, multi-stack per subdir, and 1-level-only depth enforcement.\n\n**Test results:** 76/76 tests pass in stack-detect.test.ts. Full suite: 3085/3085 pass across 114 files. Zero regressions.\n\n**Design note:** Tests use real filesystem temp directories (matching the existing test pattern in this file) rather than mocking `fs` as the story's technical notes suggested. This is more robust and consistent with the codebase.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Observations:** The story's technical notes suggested mocking `readdirSync` and `existsSync` via `vi.mock('node:fs')`, but the existing test file uses real temp directories with `mkdtempSync`. I followed the existing pattern for consistency -- real filesystem tests are more reliable and the test file already had the infrastructure for it. No mocking needed.\n- **Observations:** AC2 specifies the return order as `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: 'frontend' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: 'backend' }]`, but the actual correct order per AC6 (sorted alphabetically by dir name) is `backend` before `frontend`. The implementation follows AC6's ordering rule, and the test validates the alphabetically-sorted order `[backend, frontend]`. If the caller truly expects `frontend` first, that would be a spec inconsistency in the story."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a10fc6fe66058bdcf (use SendMessage with to: 'a10fc6fe66058bdcf' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 44013\ntool_uses: 22\nduration_ms: 150309</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"920d100a-a3f1-41ed-bf53-d85a660ba553","uuid":"286e489c-dadf-4905-bb1c-a207e611c150","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:08:29.949Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-dev-story for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-1-multi-stack-detection-subdir-scanning.md — implement all tasks, write tests, and mark the story for review. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously through all tasks until complete. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, unclear task specs, missing APIs)\n- Workarounds applied (anything hacky, copied patterns that felt wrong, TODOs left behind)\n- Code quality concerns (areas that need refactoring, edge cases not handled, tech debt added)\n- Observations (unexpected complexity, architectural mismatches, dependency issues)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a10fc6fe66058bdcf","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Implementation complete. Here is a summary:\n\n**Story 9-1: Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning** -- Status: **review**\n\n**What was done:**\n\n1. **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/stack-detect.ts`** -- Added `StackDetection` interface, `SKIP_DIRS` constant (7 dirs), `STACK_MARKERS` constant (priority-ordered), `detectStacks()` function with root + 1-level subdirectory scanning. Refactored `detectStack()` to delegate to `detectStacks()` as a compat wrapper.\n\n2. **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`** -- Added 15 new tests in a `detectStacks` describe block covering all 6 acceptance criteria: dual/triple root stacks, monorepo layout, single-stack, empty dir, all 7 skip dirs, priority ordering, alphabetical subdir sorting, python marker deduplication, multi-stack per subdir, and 1-level-only depth enforcement.\n\n**Test results:** 76/76 tests pass in stack-detect.test.ts. Full suite: 3085/3085 pass across 114 files. Zero regressions.\n\n**Design note:** Tests use real filesystem temp directories (matching the existing test pattern in this file) rather than mocking `fs` as the story's technical notes suggested. This is more robust and consistent with the codebase.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Observations:** The story's technical notes suggested mocking `readdirSync` and `existsSync` via `vi.mock('node:fs')`, but the existing test file uses real temp directories with `mkdtempSync`. I followed the existing pattern for consistency -- real filesystem tests are more reliable and the test file already had the infrastructure for it. No mocking needed.\n- **Observations:** AC2 specifies the return order as `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: 'frontend' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: 'backend' }]`, but the actual correct order per AC6 (sorted alphabetically by dir name) is `backend` before `frontend`. The implementation follows AC6's ordering rule, and the test validates the alphabetically-sorted order `[backend, frontend]`. If the caller truly expects `frontend` first, that would be a spec inconsistency in the story."}],"totalDurationMs":150309,"totalTokens":44013,"totalToolUseCount":22,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1854,"cache_read_input_tokens":41588,"output_tokens":570,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral