{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Cxxc3JMDGP4TtKB29uGny5","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All done. Here is the review summary.\n\n---\n\n**Code Review: Story 9-1 — Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning**\n\n**Story:** `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-1-multi-stack-detection-subdir-scanning.md`\n**Files reviewed:** `src/lib/stack-detect.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`\n**Git vs Story discrepancies:** 0 (git confirms exactly the 2 files claimed)\n\n### Issues Found and Fixed\n\n**1. HIGH — `detectStack()` compat wrapper silently changed behavior**\nThe old `detectStack()` only checked root-level files. The refactored version delegated to `detectStacks()` which also scans subdirectories, meaning `detectStack()` could return a stack from a subdirectory when it previously returned `null`. This would break callers (`init-project.ts`, `state.ts`, `coverage.ts`, `env.ts`) that assume the returned stack applies to the root directory.\n**Fix:** Added `.find((s) => s.dir === '.')` filter so `detectStack()` only returns root-level stacks. Added test confirming subdir-only projects return `null`.\n\n**2. HIGH — SKIP_DIRS incomplete, causing false-positive Python detection**\nMissing `.venv`, `venv`, `.tox`, `.mypy_cache`, `.cache`. Python virtual environments (`.venv`/`venv`) contain `setup.py`, `pyproject.toml`, and other Python markers, leading to false-positive stack detections. `.tox` contains test envs with similar markers.\n**Fix:** Added 5 directories to `SKIP_DIRS`. Added 2 new tests covering these skip entries.\n\n**3. MEDIUM — `StackDetection.stack` typed as `string` instead of union**\nLoses type safety — callers can't rely on exhaustive checking against known stacks.\n**Fix:** Added `StackName = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'rust'` type; applied to `StackDetection.stack` and `STACK_MARKERS`.\n\n**4. MEDIUM — Unused `StackDetection` type import in test file**\nDead import on line 6 of the test file.\n**Fix:** Removed the unused import.\n\n### Results After Fixes\n\n- **Tests:** 79 pass in stack-detect.test.ts (76 original + 3 new), 3088 pass across full suite\n- **Coverage:** 97.05% overall (above 90% target), all 123 files above 80% per-file floor\n- **Regressions:** Zero\n- **Story status:** Updated to `verifying`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n- HIGH: `detectStack()` compat wrapper returned subdirectory stacks, breaking root-only callers\n- HIGH: SKIP_DIRS missing 5 common tool/venv directories causing false-positive Python detection\n- MEDIUM: `stack` field typed as `string` instead of `StackName` union\n- MEDIUM: Unused type import in test file\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- `readdirSync` with `isDirectory()` follows symlinks — a symlink to an external directory could cause scanning outside the project tree. Low risk in practice.\n- `detectStack()` return type is `string | null` not `StackName | null` — changing it would require updating all downstream callers (story 9-2 through 9-5 scope, not this story).\n- The inline `import('node:fs').Dirent[]` type annotation on line 56 is unusual; a top-level import of the `Dirent` type would be cleaner.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- No test for `detectStacks()` called with a non-existent directory path (the `catch` branch on line 59 is exercised only implicitly).\n- No test for `detectStacks()` when a scanned subdirectory contains a symlink to a directory with stack markers.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- `detectStack()` now internally calls `detectStacks()` which does a full subdirectory scan even though it only uses root results. Minor perf concern for projects with many subdirectories. Acceptable for now.\n- The tech spec says `detectStack()` should return the first element of `detectStacks()` (`stacks[0]?.stack`), but the review fix changed it to filter root-only. The tech spec should be updated to match, or downstream consumers in stories 9-2 through 9-5 need to be aware of this divergence.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:** None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a13a3a4b7a8a484be (use SendMessage with to: 'a13a3a4b7a8a484be' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 53513\ntool_uses: 39\nduration_ms: 228636</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"920d100a-a3f1-41ed-bf53-d85a660ba553","uuid":"481fa151-0612-4ae8-ba39-abae4c04472a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:12:44.999Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-1-multi-stack-detection-subdir-scanning.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a13a3a4b7a8a484be","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All done. Here is the review summary.\n\n---\n\n**Code Review: Story 9-1 — Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning**\n\n**Story:** `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-1-multi-stack-detection-subdir-scanning.md`\n**Files reviewed:** `src/lib/stack-detect.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`\n**Git vs Story discrepancies:** 0 (git confirms exactly the 2 files claimed)\n\n### Issues Found and Fixed\n\n**1. HIGH — `detectStack()` compat wrapper silently changed behavior**\nThe old `detectStack()` only checked root-level files. The refactored version delegated to `detectStacks()` which also scans subdirectories, meaning `detectStack()` could return a stack from a subdirectory when it previously returned `null`. This would break callers (`init-project.ts`, `state.ts`, `coverage.ts`, `env.ts`) that assume the returned stack applies to the root directory.\n**Fix:** Added `.find((s) => s.dir === '.')` filter so `detectStack()` only returns root-level stacks. Added test confirming subdir-only projects return `null`.\n\n**2. HIGH — SKIP_DIRS incomplete, causing false-positive Python detection**\nMissing `.venv`, `venv`, `.tox`, `.mypy_cache`, `.cache`. Python virtual environments (`.venv`/`venv`) contain `setup.py`, `pyproject.toml`, and other Python markers, leading to false-positive stack detections. `.tox` contains test envs with similar markers.\n**Fix:** Added 5 directories to `SKIP_DIRS`. Added 2 new tests covering these skip entries.\n\n**3. MEDIUM — `StackDetection.stack` typed as `string` instead of union**\nLoses type safety — callers can't rely on exhaustive checking against known stacks.\n**Fix:** Added `StackName = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'rust'` type; applied to `StackDetection.stack` and `STACK_MARKERS`.\n\n**4. MEDIUM — Unused `StackDetection` type import in test file**\nDead import on line 6 of the test file.\n**Fix:** Removed the unused import.\n\n### Results After Fixes\n\n- **Tests:** 79 pass in stack-detect.test.ts (76 original + 3 new), 3088 pass across full suite\n- **Coverage:** 97.05% overall (above 90% target), all 123 files above 80% per-file floor\n- **Regressions:** Zero\n- **Story status:** Updated to `verifying`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n- HIGH: `detectStack()` compat wrapper returned subdirectory stacks, breaking root-only callers\n- HIGH: SKIP_DIRS missing 5 common tool/venv directories causing false-positive Python detection\n- MEDIUM: `stack` field typed as `string` instead of `StackName` union\n- MEDIUM: Unused type import in test file\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- `readdirSync` with `isDirectory()` follows symlinks — a symlink to an external directory could cause scanning outside the project tree. Low risk in practice.\n- `detectStack()` return type is `string | null` not `StackName | null` — changing it would require updating all downstream callers (story 9-2 through 9-5 scope, not this story).\n- The inline `import('node:fs').Dirent[]` type annotation on line 56 is unusual; a top-level import of the `Dirent` type would be cleaner.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- No test for `detectStacks()` called with a non-existent directory path (the `catch` branch on line 59 is exercised only implicitly).\n- No test for `detectStacks()` when a scanned subdirectory contains a symlink to a directory with stack markers.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- `detectStack()` now internally calls `detectStacks()` which does a full subdirectory scan even though it only uses root results. Minor perf concern for projects with many subdirectories. Acceptable for now.\n- The tech spec says `detectStack()` should return the first element of `detectStacks()` (`stacks[0]?.stack`), but the review fix changed it to filter root-only. The tech spec should be updated to match, or downstream consumers in stories 9-2 through 9-5 need to be aware of this divergence.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:** None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed."}],"totalDurationMs":228636,"totalTokens":53513,"totalToolUseCount":39,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":456,"cache_read_input_tokens":51948,"output_tokens":1108,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4