{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YJ1vMowW4v1Ae1XJTKBsKV","type":"tool_result","content":"  1092→## 4. What Went Wrong\n  1093→\n  1094→- **HIGH bug shipped from dev-story to review.** The transport/port mismatch was introduced during implementation in session 3 and was not caught by unit tests. Unit tests validate code behavior but not template correctness — the template is a markdown file containing code snippets, so runtime correctness depends on human or LLM review.\n  1095→- **Template content had no automated validation.** The `rust.md` template contained incorrect Rust code that would compile but produce wrong runtime behavior. There are no tests that validate template content against the actual env var values written by the code.\n  1096→- **NFR1 (300-line file limit) continues to be violated.** `otlp.ts` grew from 375 to 423 lines across sessions 3-4 with no refactoring. The duplication between `ensureServiceNameEnvVar` and `ensureEndpointEnvVar` was noted but not addressed.\n  1097→- **Pre-existing sprint module test failures remain unaddressed** after 4 sessions. They are unrelated to Epic 8 work but reduce confidence in the test suite.\n  1098→\n  1099→---\n  1100→\n  1101→## 5. Lessons Learned\n  1102→\n  1103→1. **Template files need review-time scrutiny.** Markdown templates containing code snippets are not covered by unit tests. The code review step is the primary quality gate for template correctness. Consider adding a lint or validation step that cross-references template content with code constants (e.g., verifying port numbers match).\n  1104→2. **Transport protocol and port must be consistent.** gRPC uses 4317, HTTP uses 4318. When a template specifies one transport, the env var must use the matching port. This is a common OTLP gotcha.\n  1105→3. **The review gate works.** Session 3 left the story at `review` rather than forcing it to `done`. Session 4's review found a real bug. The multi-step pipeline (dev -> review -> verify) adds latency but catches real problems.\n  1106→4. **Tech debt accumulates when \"accepted\" repeatedly.** The NFR1 violation was noted in sessions 3 and 4 but not fixed either time. Each session adds more lines. A dedicated cleanup story would be more effective than hoping it gets addressed incidentally.\n  1107→\n  1108→---\n  1109→\n  1110→## 6. Action Items\n  1111→\n  1112→| # | Action | Priority | Owner |\n  1113→|---|--------|----------|-------|\n  1114→| 1 | Refactor `otlp.ts`: extract generic `ensureEnvVar()` helper to reduce duplication and line count | MEDIUM | Next sprint or story 8-8 |\n  1115→| 2 | Investigate and fix 6 pre-existing sprint module test failures | MEDIUM | Tech debt backlog |\n  1116→| 3 | Add template validation: cross-reference port numbers in templates vs. code constants | LOW | Tech debt backlog |\n  1117→| 4 | Add guardrail to prevent dev-story agent from overwriting sprint-status.yaml | MEDIUM | Ralph configuration |\n  1118→| 5 | Consider splitting `coverage.ts` (568 lines) into sub-modules | LOW | Tech debt backlog |\n  1119→\n  1120→---\n  1121→\n  1122→## Session 4 Final Metrics\n  1123→\n  1124→| Metric | Value |\n  1125→|--------|-------|\n  1126→| Stories attempted this window | 1 (8-7) |\n  1127→| Stories completed this window | 1 (8-7 review -> done) |\n  1128→| Stories completed total (full day) | 7 (8-1 through 8-7) |\n  1129→| Stories failed | 0 |\n  1130→| Bugs found this window | 3 (1 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM) — all fixed |\n  1131→| Bugs found total (full day) | 24 |\n  1132→| Test count | 3014 |\n  1133→| Coverage | 97% |\n  1134→| Sprint progress | 32/34 done, 2 backlog (94%) |\n  1135→| Epics completed (full day) | 3 full (8.1, 8.2, 8.3), 1 half (8.4: 1/2 done) |\n  1136→| Remaining | 8-8 (backlog), 8-9 (backlog) |\n  1137→| Key risk | otlp.ts NFR1 violation growing unchecked |\n  1138→| Top tech debt | otlp.ts 423 lines, coverage.ts 568 lines, 6 failing sprint tests |\n  1139→\n  1140→---\n  1141→\n  1142→# Session 5 Retrospective — 2026-03-23T12:10Z\n  1143→\n  1144→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence Sprint\n  1145→**Session window:** ~12:10 - 12:30 UTC (~20 minutes)\n  1146→**Ralph iteration:** 10\n  1147→**Commits produced:** 1 (`b1dd9c0`)\n  1148→\n  1149→---\n  1150→\n  1151→## 1. Session Summary\n  1152→\n  1153→| Story | Phase | Outcome | Duration | Notes |\n  1154→|-------|-------|---------|----------|-------|\n  1155→| 8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding | create-story | done | ~3 min (12:11-12:14) | ACs 1-3 already implemented by earlier stories; only AC4 was new work |\n  1156→| 8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding | dev-story | done | ~3.5 min (12:14-12:18) | 28 docs-scaffold tests added, 3018 vitest + 307 BATS all pass |\n  1157→| 8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding | code-review | done | ~4 min (12:18-12:22) | 2 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM, 2 LOW findings; 4 fixed, 2 accepted |\n  1158→| 8-8-rust-documentation-scaffolding | verification | done | ~6.5 min (12:22-12:29) | 7/7 ACs passed |\n  1159→\n  1160→One story attempted, one completed. Epic 8.4 (Rust Observability & Docs) is now fully done. This was the final story that Ralph could pick up — only 8-9 (semgrep rules for Rust) remains in backlog.\n  1161→\n  1162→---\n  1163→\n  1164→## 2. Issues Analysis\n  1165→\n  1166→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Review\n  1167→\n  1168→| Severity | Issue | Fixed? |\n  1169→|----------|-------|--------|\n  1170→| HIGH | Cargo.toml regex only matched double-quoted values; single quotes are valid TOML | Yes |\n  1171→| HIGH | Cargo.toml section regex broke on `[` characters inside values; used `[\\s\\S]*?` with lookahead | Yes |\n  1172→| MEDIUM | Test assertion for dependencies-only Cargo.toml was too weak — didn't verify actual fallback value | Yes |\n  1173→| MEDIUM | No test for `[package]` section with no `name` field | Yes (test added) |\n  1174→\n  1175→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt)\n  1176→\n  1177→| Item | Detail |\n  1178→|------|--------|\n  1179→| Mixed-quote regex | Regex doesn't enforce matching open/close quotes (e.g., `name = 'foo\"` would parse). Accepted per NFR3 — simple parser, not a TOML spec implementation. |\n  1180→| Pre-existing uncovered lines | Lines 180, 221-222 in docs-scaffold.ts remain uncovered — pre-existing, not introduced by 8-8. |\n  1181→| sprint-status.yaml not auto-updated | Agent couldn't update sprint-status.yaml during create-story phase; required manual update to `ready-for-dev`. Same issue seen in earlier sessions. |\n  1182→\n  1183→### Verification Gaps\n  1184→\n  1185→| AC | Gap | Severity |\n  1186→|----|-----|----------|\n  1187→| AC1-AC6 | No log/observability events detected — these are pure utility functions with no instrumentation. Expected for documentation scaffolding, but means zero runtime observability. | LOW |\n  1188→| AC7 (test coverage) | Verified indirectly — test source files not shipped in npm package, so vitest/bats couldn't run in verification container. Relied on dev agent's test report + all 6 functional ACs passing. | MEDIUM |\n  1189→\n  1190→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n  1191→\n  1192→None this session. Clean execution.\n  1193→\n  1194→---\n  1195→\n  1196→## 3. What Went Well\n  1197→\n  1198→- **Full pipeline in 20 minutes.** Story went from backlog to done (create -> dev -> review -> verify) in a single Ralph iteration with no retries or failures.\n  1199→- **Code review caught real bugs.** The double-quote-only and section-boundary regex issues were legitimate parsing bugs that would have caused failures on real Cargo.toml files. Both fixed before verification.\n  1200→- **Creative verification approach.** Verifier wrote a `verify-acs.mjs` script to import functions directly from the dist bundle — effective workaround for the test-files-not-in-npm-package limitation.\n  1201→- **ACs 1-3 pre-implemented.** Earlier stories (8-1 through 8-7) had already added `getStackLabel('rust')`, `getCoverageTool('rust')`, and the Rust branch in `generateAgentsMdContent()`. Story 8-8 only needed to add Cargo.toml project name parsing. Good incremental architecture.\n  1202→- **Test count grew.** 3014 -> 3021 tests (net +7 from 28 new docs-scaffold tests minus pre-existing adjustments).\n  1203→- **Zero regressions.** All 3021 vitest tests and 307 BATS tests pass.\n  1204→\n  1205→---\n  1206→\n  1207→## 4. What Went Wrong\n  1208→\n  1209→- **sprint-status.yaml still not auto-updated by agents.** This has been a recurring issue across multiple sessions. The create-story agent sets status to `ready-for-dev` in its output but doesn't write to sprint-status.yaml. Not blocking (Ralph handles it), but creates state drift between the YAML and actual execution.\n  1210→- **Observability gap on pure utility functions.** The docs-scaffold functions have zero instrumentation. While this is acceptable for scaffolding utilities, it means any failures in production would be invisible. Pattern to watch as more utility functions are added.\n  1211→\n  1212→---\n  1213→\n  1214→## 5. Lessons Learned\n  1215→\n  1216→### Patterns to Repeat\n  1217→\n  1218→- **Incremental story design pays off.** Because earlier stories already handled the core Rust integration points, story 8-8 was small and focused. The create-story agent correctly identified that ACs 1-3 were already done — no wasted work.\n  1219→- **Code review as quality gate.** 2 HIGH bugs caught and fixed before verification. Without review, these would have been shipped as latent bugs in Cargo.toml parsing.\n  1220→- **Single-iteration completion.** When stories are well-scoped and prerequisites are met, the full pipeline (create/dev/review/verify) completes in one pass. No retries, no stuck stories.\n  1221→\n  1222→### Patterns to Avoid\n  1223→\n  1224→- **Regex-based TOML parsing.** Works for the simple case but accumulates edge-case bugs (quotes, section boundaries, comments). If Cargo.toml parsing grows beyond `name` extraction, switch to a proper TOML parser.\n  1225→- **Indirect test verification.** AC7 was verified indirectly because test files aren't in the npm package. If more stories depend on test execution in the verification container, need to address the packaging gap.\n  1226→\n  1227→---\n  1228→\n  1229→## 6. Action Items\n  1230→\n  1231→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n  1232→\n  1233→- None. Story 8-8 is clean and verified.\n  1234→\n  1235→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint)\n  1236→\n  1237→| Item | Priority | Detail |\n  1238→|------|----------|--------|\n  1239→| sprint-status.yaml agent auto-update | MEDIUM | Agents should write status changes to sprint-status.yaml, not just log them. Recurring issue across 5 sessions. |\n  1240→| docs-scaffold.ts uncovered lines | LOW | Lines 180, 221-222 remain uncovered. Pre-existing but should be addressed. |\n  1241→\n  1242→### Backlog\n  1243→\n  1244→| Item | Detail |\n  1245→|------|--------|\n  1246→| TOML parser for Cargo.toml | If Cargo.toml parsing expands beyond `name`, replace regex with a proper parser (e.g., `@iarna/toml` or similar). |\n  1247→| Utility function observability policy | Decide whether pure utility functions (docs-scaffold, etc.) need instrumentation or if the current zero-observability stance is acceptable. |\n  1248→| 8-9 semgrep rules for Rust | Last remaining story in Epic 8. Blocked on semgrep rule authoring for Rust-specific observability patterns. |\n  1249→| otlp.ts / coverage.ts file size | Carried forward: otlp.ts 423 lines, coverage.ts 568 lines — both exceed NFR1 limits. |\n  1250→\n  1251→---\n  1252→\n  1253→## Session 5 Final Metrics\n  1254→\n  1255→| Metric | Value |\n  1256→|--------|-------|\n  1257→| Stories attempted this window | 1 (8-8) |\n  1258→| Stories completed this window | 1 (8-8) |\n  1259→| Stories completed total (full day) | 8 (8-1 through 8-8) |\n  1260→| Stories failed | 0 |\n  1261→| Bugs found this window | 4 (2 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM) — all fixed |\n  1262→| Bugs found total (full day) | 28 |\n  1263→| Test count | 3021 |\n  1264→| Sprint progress | 33/34 done, 1 backlog (97%) |\n  1265→| Epics completed (full day) | 4 full (8.1, 8.2, 8.3, 8.4) |\n  1266→| Remaining | 8-9 (backlog) |\n  1267→| Key risk | otlp.ts NFR1 violation growing unchecked |\n  1268→| Top tech debt | otlp.ts 423 lines, coverage.ts 568 lines, regex-based TOML parsing |\n  1269→\n  1270→---\n  1271→\n  1272→# Session 6 Retrospective — 2026-03-23T12:32Z\n  1273→\n  1274→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence Sprint\n  1275→**Session window:** ~12:32 UTC (session 6, final session of the day)\n  1276→**Stories in scope:** 8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability\n  1277→**Ralph iterations:** loop 11, calls 9/100\n  1278→\n  1279→---\n  1280→\n  1281→## 1. Session Summary\n  1282→\n  1283→| Story | Phase Reached | Outcome | Notes |\n  1284→|-------|--------------|---------|-------|\n  1285→| 8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability | create-story -> dev -> code-review -> verification | **FAILED (AC2)** — returned to `in-progress` | AC2 invalid Semgrep Rust pattern syntax; AC1, AC3, AC4 passed |\n  1286→\n  1287→One story attempted, zero completed. Story 8-9 made it through all four pipeline phases but failed verification on AC2. The Semgrep rule `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` contains invalid Rust pattern syntax — match arms written as standalone expressions, which Semgrep cannot parse. Story sent back to `in-progress`.\n  1288→\n  1289→---\n  1290→\n  1291→## 2. Issues Analysis"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01MMuf4b7jRDkQhB3HyTW1f7","session_id":"920d100a-a3f1-41ed-bf53-d85a660ba553","uuid":"9c421f38-3e2d-4af1-b9aa-d69f81c01692","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:19:19.287Z"}
